  "number": "3.1",
  "title": "General Solutions",
  "body": "General Solutions   Let's consider two more examples to illustrate the concept of a differential equation and what it means to \"solve\" a differential equation.  A Calculus Perspective  Suppose you were given , and asked to find .   Since we are familiar with calculus, we quickly take two derivatives of , giving   This task is no problem for us, but suppose we started with and were asked to go in the reverse direction. That is, find a function, , that has as a second derivative. This is precisely what solving a differential equation aims to do and we would phrase this problem as,    \"given the differential equation, , solve for \"    A Physics Perspective  Let be the position of some object at time, . Assume for the moment that we don't know what is, but we do know the object is moving with a constant velocity of meters per second.  Physics tells us that velocity is the rate of change of position (i.e., derivative of position, ). So, given that the object is moving at a known constant velocity, we may write   This is another example of a differential equation where one could ask \"what function, , has a derivative that is equal to ?\"   The situations above illustrate simple examples of what a differential differential equation is and what it means to \"solve\" a differential equation. Throughout this text, we will present many more examples and discuss various techniques used to solve them.   Examples   General Solutions   "
